sql:
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM network_predictions
WHERE predicted_latency > 100;

external_knowledge:
Area of interest refers to 'location_name'; 
Specified timeframe refers to the period between 'start_date' and 'end_date';
High level of certainty refers to a confidence level greater than LIKELIHOOD(0.9, 0.9375);
The forecast details include prediction ID, predicted cost, actual cost, predicted latency, actual latency, predicted reliability, and actual reliability;
Additional reference points are the timestamp, location, and network segment ID.

- "overly pessimistic about the reliability" refers to predicted reliability being less than 0.5;
- "cost overestimation of more than 10 units" means the average difference between the predicted and actual costs is greater than 10;
- "most recent predictions" means selecting the most recent entry based on the timestamp for each prediction_id;
- "high confidence" means the confidence level of the prediction is greater than 0.9.

- "levels of problem seriousness" refers to the severity level of anomalies;
- "versions of the model" relate to the model version used in predictions;
- "number of issues found" corresponds to the count of anomalies.

sql:
SELECT location 
FROM network_predictions 
WHERE confidence_level < 0.9;

SELECT u.user_name, dr.report_name
FROM users u
INNER JOIN dashboard_reports dr ON u.user_id = dr.user_id;

